layout: layouts/base.njk
title: "Report \u2014 DSG: Does Fine-Tuning a Small Model Help on Swiss Data Protection?"
description: "A reproducible four-way ablation (base / +RAG / fine-tuned / both) of Apertus-8B on Swiss Federal Act on Data Protection (revised FADP / nDSG) (SR 235.1) Q&A, scored deterministically on answer accuracy and exact article citation. No LLM judge."
tags: writing
resType: report
date: 2026-07-20
kicker: Report
listTitle: "Swiss Data Protection: does fine-tuning a small model help?"
blurb: "A reproducible four-way ablation of Apertus-8B on Swiss data protection Q&A over the Federal Act on Data Protection (revised FADP / nDSG) (SR 235.1). Fine-tuning plus retrieval takes the production bar (answer + exact citation) from 37.0% to 54.3% \u2014 deterministic scoring, public Fedlex data, harness open-sourced. Industry: Government & Public Sector."
faq:
  - q: "Is this on our data?"
    a: "No \u2014 deliberately. It runs entirely on the public, pinned Fedlex text of the DSG so anyone can reproduce it. In a Pilot the identical method runs on your documents, inside your environment, and the report stays yours."
  - q: "Why does fine-tuning alone (arm C) fail?"
    a: "Because a small model can't reliably recall exact article numbers from parameters. The fine-tune teaches the answer/citation format and which article governs which topic, but the exact citation still needs the retrieved text in front of it. That is why the winning system is fine-tuning plus retrieval, not either alone."
  - q: "Is there an LLM judge?"
    a: "No LLM judge anywhere. The DSG numbers its articles; a correct citation is exactly checkable. Answer accuracy is string/number matching against a verified gold answer; citation is an exact article match. Every number is recomputed from frozen run records with 95% Wilson intervals."
---
